aa(lp85
VNow, at Global Witness,
p86
aVwe wanted to see what this actually looked like in practice.
p87
aVHow does this actually work?
p88
aVSo what we did
p89
aVis we sent in an undercover investigator to 13 Manhattan law firms.
p90
aVOur investigator posed as an African minister
p91
aVwho wanted to move suspect funds into the United States
p92
aVto buy a house, a yacht, a jet.
p93
aVNow, what was truly shocking was that all but one of those lawyers
p94
aVprovided our investigator with suggestions
p95
aVon how to move those suspect funds.
p96
aVThese were all preliminary meetings,
p97
aVand none of the lawyers took us on as a client
p98
aVand of course no money moved hands,
p99
aVbut it really shows the problem with the system.
p100
aa(lp101
VIt's also important
p102
aVto not just think about this as individual cases.
p103
aVThis is not just about an individual lawyer
p104
aVwho's spoken to our undercover investigator and provided suggestions.
p105
aVIt's not just about a particular senior politician
p106
aVwho's been caught up in a scandal.
p107
aVThis is about how a system works,
p108
aVthat entrenches corruption, tax evasion, poverty and instability.
p109
aVAnd in order to tackle this,
p110
aVwe need to change the game.
p111
aVWe need to change the rules of the game
p112
aVto make this sort of behavior harder.
p113
aa(lp114
VThis may seem like doom and gloom,
p115
aVlike there's nothing we can do about it,
p116
aVlike nothing has ever changed,
p117
aVlike there will always be rich and powerful individuals.
p118
aVBut as a natural optimist,
p119
aVI do see that we are starting to get some change.
p120
aa(lp121
VOver the last couple of years,
p122
aVwe've seen a real push towards greater transparency
p123
aVwhen it comes to company ownership.
p124
aVThis issue was put on the political agenda
p125
aVby the UK Prime Minister David Cameron
p126
aVat a big G8 Summit that was held in Northern Ireland in 2013.
p127
aVAnd since then, the European Union is going to be creating
p128
aVcentral registers at a national level
p129
aVof who really owns and controls companies across Europe.
p130
aa(lp131
VOne of the things that is sad is that, actually, the US is lagging behind.
p132
aVThere's bipartisan legislation that had been introduced
p133
aVin the House and the Senate,
p134
aVbut it isn't making as much progress as we'd like to see.
p135
aVSo we'd really want to see the Panama leaks,
p136
aVthis huge peek into the offshore world,
p137
aVbe used as a way of opening up in the US and around the world.
p138
aa(lp139
VFor us at Global Witness, this is a moment for change.
p140
aVWe need ordinary people to get angry
p141
aVat the way in which people can hide their identity
p142
aVbehind secret companies.
p143
aVWe need business leaders to stand up and say,
p144
aV"Secrecy like this is not good for business."
p145
aVWe need political leaders to recognize the problem,
p146
aVand to commit to changing the law to open up this sort of secrecy.
p147
aa(lp148
VTogether, we can end the secrecy
p149
aVthat is currently allowing tax evasion,
p150
aVcorruption, money laundering to flourish.
